 this volume discusses and illustrates about 25% of the species in every family, including the tiny species, making this the most comprehensive volume in its field. With this approach it provides access to microlepidoptera study for biologists as well as amateur collectors. About 2,500 species are described and illustrated, including virtually all moths of economic importance, summarizing their morphology, taxonomy, adult behavior, larval biology, and life cycles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMothszNorthwest, Canadian. 0aMothszWest (U.S.). 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Entomology.2bisacsh  aamateur collectors.  abiologists.  acomprehensive account.  acrop damage.  adamaging insects.  adefoliating forests.  aillustrated.  ainsect biota.  ainsect damage.  ainsect diversity.  alarval biology.  alepidopterists.  amicrolepidoptera study.  amoth diets.  amoth infestations.  amoth larvae.  amoth life cycles.  amoth morphology.  amoth relationships.  amoth species.  amoth taxonomy.  amoths.  anorth america.  aplant and insect life.  aplant diets.  aregional biology.  awestern insects.  awestern north america.1 aOpler, Paul A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025197740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094377340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943773/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY